  "companies": [],
  "statement": "# 3Sum\n\nReturn all unique triplets of values in `nums` whose sum is zero. The order of triplets does not matter.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: nums = [-4, -1, -1, 0, 1, 2]\nOutput: [[-1, -1, 2], [-1, 0, 1]]\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: nums = [0, 0, 0, 0]\nOutput: [[0, 0, 0]]\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: nums = [1, 2, -2, -1]\nOutput: []\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- `0 <= len(nums) <= 3000`\n- `-10^5 <= nums[i] <= 10^5`",
  "editorial": "Sort the array. Fix one value, then solve the remaining two-value search with two pointers while skipping duplicates.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def threeSum(self, nums):\n        nums.sort()\n        result = []\n        for i, value in enumerate(nums):\n            if i and value == nums[i - 1]:\n                continue\n            left, right = i + 1, len(nums) - 1\n            while left < right:\n                total = value + nums[left] + nums[right]\n                if total == 0:\n                    result.append([value, nums[left], nums[right]])\n                    left += 1\n                    right -= 1\n                    while left < right and nums[left] == nums[left - 1]:\n                        left += 1\n                    while left < right and nums[right] == nums[right + 1]:\n                        right -= 1\n                elif total < 0:\n                    left += 1\n                else:\n                    right -= 1\n        return result\n```",
  "hints": [
    "Sorting makes duplicate handling and two-pointer movement easier.",
    "After fixing one value, the target for the other two is its negation."
  ],
